|CKBStreet Samurai|000

|CK0Street Samurai are cybernetic combat specialists whose Cortex OS links
signature implants into one fighting platform. Their combat rhythm is to read
the encounter, create Edge, spend it on decisive routines, and manage Heat
before the Cortex enters thermal lockout.|000

|CKBYour first steps|000
|CK0The public contract office is east of Fountain Court near Moongate Plaza.
Joining installs a prototype-grade Cortex OS automatically. The secured clinic
beyond the office is open to members and wizards; engage Rin Kade there to
inspect, purchase, install, extract, or repair signature hardware. Contract
services are covered for active members, but new hardware still costs coins.|000

|CK0A new member should run dashboard, samskills, and samhelp start. Dashboard
shows the contract, resources, strain, installed implants, and maintenance
state. Samskills shows what is unlocked and whether required hardware is
present. Samrepair is only for a damaged or incomplete guild installation; it
is not part of normal onboarding.|000

|CKBProgression and combat|000
|CK0Street Samurai earn GXP from combat and boss victories recognized by
Darkwind's shared battle progression, not by repeating firmware commands.
Guild Level unlocks routines and hardware through GL16. Cortex Rank continues
through CR200 and gradually improves the host OS after Guild Level stops
advancing.|000

|CK0Snap Cut is the most reliable early source of Edge. Threat Scan prepares a
target for Ripcut and later interacts with Monowire. Most active routines add
Heat when they succeed. Available Edge is automatically routed into stronger
versions of most routine effects, but an empty Edge pool never blocks the base
routine. Overclock trades Cortex wear for temporary thermal headroom. Use the
combat monitor, samstatus, or dashboard to decide when to press an advantage
and when to cool down.|000

|CKBWhere to look|000
|CK0Use samhelp start for onboarding, samhelp commands for the full index,
samhelp resources for Edge and Heat, samhelp firmware for routine and hardware
relationships, and samhelp maintenance when dashboard reports a problem.
Samhelp <routine> explains any active firmware command.|000
